          adult: "The sacraments are efficacious signs of grace, instituted by Christ and entrusted to the Church, by which divine life is dispensed to us (CCC 1131). They are 'powers that come forth' from the Body of Christ, like the power that healed the woman who touched his cloak; they are actions of Christ himself, working through the Holy Spirit (CCC 1116). Because Christ is the true agent, the sacraments act ex opere operato, literally 'by the very fact of the action being performed': their validity does not depend on the personal holiness of the minister (CCC 1128). Yet their fruitfulness in the recipient does depend on his or her dispositions; the sacraments presuppose faith, and they also nourish, strengthen, and express it, which is why they are called sacraments of faith (CCC 1123-1128, 1131). They are likewise sacraments 'of the Church' in a double sense: they exist by her and for her, building up the Body of Christ (CCC 1118). Three of them, Baptism, Confirmation, and Holy Orders, confer a sacramental character, an indelible spiritual mark that configures the recipient to Christ and can never be repeated or erased (CCC 1121). For believers, the sacraments of the New Covenant are necessary for salvation, because sacramental grace is the grace of the Holy Spirit given by Christ and proper to each sacrament (CCC 1129)."
