          youth: "Baptism is the first sacrament of Christian initiation, the doorway to life in the Spirit and to all the other sacraments. Its very name comes from the Greek word for plunging: to be baptized is to be plunged into Christ's death and rise with him as a new creation. God prepared this gift for centuries: the Spirit hovering over the waters at creation, the flood, the crossing of the Red Sea and the Jordan all prefigured it, and Jesus, though sinless, was baptized by John to identify with us, then commanded his apostles to baptize all nations. The celebration itself teaches you what happens: the sign of the cross, the proclamation of the Word, the renunciation of Satan and profession of faith, the water poured three times with the Trinitarian words, the anointing with chrism, the white garment, and the candle lit from the Easter candle. Anyone not yet baptized can receive this sacrament, and in an emergency anyone at all can baptize with water and the Trinitarian formula.",
          adult: "Christian initiation is accomplished by three sacraments: Baptism, which is its beginning, Confirmation, which strengthens it, and the Eucharist, which nourishes the disciple for transformation in Christ (CCC 1212). Holy Baptism is the basis of the whole Christian life, the gateway to life in the Spirit, and the door which gives access to the other sacraments (CCC 1213). It is called Baptism from the Greek baptizein, to plunge or immerse, signifying burial into Christ's death and resurrection with him; it is also called the washing of regeneration and enlightenment (CCC 1214-1216). The Old Covenant prefigured it: water at creation, Noah's ark, the crossing of the Red Sea, and the entry into the promised land through the Jordan (CCC 1217-1222). All these prefigurations are fulfilled in Christ, who began his public life by receiving John's baptism, and who after his Resurrection commanded, 'Go therefore and make disciples of all nations, baptizing them in the name of the Father and of the Son and of the Holy Spirit' (Matthew 28:19; CCC 1223). The essential rite is the triple immersion in or pouring of water with the invocation of the Trinity, surrounded by rites that unfold its meaning: the proclamation of the Word, the renunciation of sin and profession of faith, the post-baptismal anointing with chrism, the white garment, and the baptismal candle (CCC 1234-1245). Every person not yet baptized, and only such a person, is able to be baptized; in case of necessity anyone, even someone not baptized, can baptize using water and the Trinitarian formula with the intention of doing what the Church does (CCC 1246, 1256)."
